  "description": "Audience analysis is the process of determining who the reader is, what they know, what they need, and what they\u0026rsquo;re trying to do — before writing a word. In technical writing, audience analysis is not preliminary research but the foundation that every structural and stylistic decision rests on.\nKaren Schriver identified three approaches to audience analysis, each with different reliability [@schriver1997]:\nClassification-based — the writer categorizes readers by demographics, role, or expertise level (\u0026ldquo;engineers with 3+ years of experience,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;new users,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;administrators\u0026rdquo;). This is the most common approach and the least reliable, because categories obscure the variation within them. Not all \u0026ldquo;new users\u0026rdquo; know the same things or want the same outcomes.\n",
  "name": "Audience Analysis",
